                "For the Pasteur effect: draw the allosteric diagram of PFK — arrow from high ATP to PFK (inhibit); arrow from high AMP to PFK (activate). Connect O2 availability → aerobic respiration → high ATP → PFK inhibited → glycolysis slows → fermentation suppressed. Walk through the logic every time.",
                "For lactate vs lactic acid: memorise pKa = 3.86. At physiological pH 7.4, lactate dominates overwhelmingly. Write: 'In the body, we say lactate, not lactic acid.' Apply this correction every time you write about muscle physiology.",
                "For the Warburg effect: construct the two-column table: 'What Warburg IS' vs 'What Warburg IS NOT'. Biosynthetic advantage goes in IS; O2 deprivation goes in IS NOT. Require yourself to populate both columns before discussing any cancer cell metabolism question.",
                "For energy yield comparison: build the full ATP accounting table from scratch — glycolysis (2 ATP), pyruvate oxidation (0 ATP but feeds TCA), TCA (0 substrate-level ATP per turn but produces NADH/FADH2 for ETC), ETC (~26–28 ATP). Compare with fermentation (2 ATP total). Do this calculation once from first principles."
